Why is it necessary to deactivate the sensor first? Can we not do this:

```
if (sensor != nullptr && !sensor->isActive())
{
    sensor->activate(sensorPathStr, i2cDev);
}
```

```
void PSUSensor::activate(const std::string& newPath,
                         const std::shared_ptr<I2CDevice>& newI2CDevice)
{
    path = newPath;
    i2cDevice = newI2CDevice;
    inputDev.open(path, boost::asio::random_access_file::read_only);
    markAvailable(true);
    setupRead();
}
```
When calling activate(), it will pass "newPath" & "newI2CDevice" into sensor, although I don't see there two params are changed in my testing, but I think it better to do deactivate() before activate().

I think the change should be in 
activate()
{
  if (isActive()) return;
  //active code below
}

Hi @Zhikui & @Ed,

Sorry for late reply, it took me sometime to recheck your comments.

> The sensor object itself, and the dbus entries should ALWAYS instantiate, regardless of the power state. Turning the power on/off shouldn't create/destroy the sensor itself, it should only modify the underlying interfaces on the activate() call. If we need an activate() call, it needs to be handled from within the sensor object, so that when we destroy it on a config change, it does the right thing.

Base @Ed's comment, we should create all sensor objects while psusensor start and only do activete() & deactivate() when poser state changes. 

> https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/dbus-sensors/+/69162/7/src/PSUSensorMain.cpp#b300
So if there are devices requires power state to be on, this patchset will break them causing those sensors not created sometime.

And from @Zhikui's comment, there might have some sensors not create initially due to the power state was off and those sensors will only be created when power state changes from off to on.

